e Americas where the trading companies set up operation, Dutch ministers sought to convert “pagans,” “Moors,” Jews, and Catholics and to spread the cultural influence of Protestant Christianity. As Dutch ministers labored under the auspices of the trading companies, the missionary project coalesced, sometimes grudgingly but often readily, with empire building and mercantile capitalism. Simultaneously, Calvinism became entangled with societies around the world as encounters with indigenous societies shaped the development of European religious and intellectual history. Though historians have traditionally treated the Protestant and European expansion as unrelated developments, the global reach of Dutch Calvinism offers a unique opportunity to understand the intermingling of a Protestant faith, commerce, and empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCalvinismzIndonesia. 0aCalvinismzNetherlandsxHistoryy17th century. 0aCalvinismzNetherlandsxHistoryy18th century. 0aCapitalismxReligious aspectsxProtestant churches. 0aImperialism. 0aMissionszIndonesia. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Western.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074977940uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300262605zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300262605423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300262605/original  a978-3-11-074977-9  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles